Data Visualization with GGPlot

by Jeon Lee on January 9, 2019

Basics

ggplot2 is based on the grammar of graphics, the idea that you can build every graph from the same few components: a data set, a set of geoms-visual marks that represent data points, and a coordinate system.

To display data values, map variables in the data set to aesthetic properties of the geom like size, color, and x and y locations.

Build a graph with qplot() or ggplot().

<Example of qplot()>

It creates a complete plot with given data, geom, and mappings. Supplies many useful defaults.

Add a new layer to a plot with a geom_() or stat_() function. Each provides a geom, a set of aesthetic mappings, and a default stat and position adjustment.

<Example of ggplot()>

Scatterplots

1. Basic scatterplot

p1 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight))
# Print plot with default points
p1 + geom_point()

2. Change color of points

p2 <- p1 + geom_point(color = "red")  #set one color for all points
p3 <- p1 + geom_point(aes(color = Height))  #set color scale by a continuous variable
p4 <- p1 + geom_point(aes(color = factor(Sex)))  #set color scale by a factor variable

grid.arrange(p2, p3, p4, nrow = 3)

# Change default colors in color scale
p1 + geom_point(aes(color = factor(Sex))) + scale_color_manual(values = c("royalblue","orangered"))

for different color names, refer to here

3. Change shape or size of points

p2 <- p1 + geom_point(size = 2.5)  #increase all points to size 2.5
p3 <- p1 + geom_point(aes(size = Height))  #set point size by continuous variable
p4 <- p1 + geom_point(aes(shape = factor(Sex)))  #set point shape by factor variable

grid.arrange(p2, p3, p4, nrow = 3)

# change the default shapes
p1 + geom_point(aes(shape = factor(Sex))) + scale_shape_manual(values = c(0,2))

FYI, the symbol table is available here:

4. Add lines to scatterplot

p2 <- p1 + geom_point(color = "blue") + geom_line()  #connect points with line
p3 <- p1 + geom_point(color = "red") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE)  #add regression line
p4 <- p1 + geom_point() + geom_vline(xintercept = 55, color = "red")  #add vertical line

grid.arrange(p2, p3, p4, nrow = 1)

# take out the points, and just create a line plot, and change size and color as before
ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + geom_line(size = 2, aes(color = factor(Sex)))

5. Change axis labels

p2 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + geom_point()

# label all axes at once
p3 <- p2 + labs(x = "Height(in)", y = "Weight(lb)")

# label and change font size
p4 <- p2 + theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 20)) + labs(x = "Height(in)")

# adjust axis limits and breaks
p5 <- p2 + scale_x_continuous("Height(in)", limits = c(50, 74), breaks = seq(50,75,5))

grid.arrange(p3, p4, p5, nrow = 3)

6. Change legend options

g1<-ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + geom_point(aes(color=factor(Sex)))
#move legend inside
g2 <- g1 + theme(legend.position=c(1,1),legend.justification=c(1,1))
g2

#move legend bottom
g3 <- g1 + theme(legend.position = "bottom")
g3

#change labels
g4 <- g1 + scale_color_discrete(name ="Sex", labels=c("Female", "Male"))
g4

# grid.arrange(g2, g3, g4, nrow=3)
g5<-ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + geom_point(size=2, aes(color = Weight))
g5 + scale_color_continuous(name="Weight", #name of legend 
                            breaks = with(my_data, c(min(Weight), mean(Weight), max(Weight))), #choose breaks of variable
                            labels = c("Light", "Medium", "Heavy"), #label
                            low = "pink",  #color of lowest value
                            high = "red"  #color of highest value
                            )

7. Change background color and style

g2 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + geom_point()

# Completely clear all lines except axis lines and make background white
t1 <- theme(plot.background = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.border = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(),
            axis.line = element_line(size = 0.4))

# Use theme to change axis label style
t2 <- theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 10),
            axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 10),
            plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 12))

g3 <- g2 + t1
g4 <- g2 + theme_bw()
g5 <- g2 + theme_bw() + t2 + labs(x = "Height(in)", y = "Weight(lb)", title = "Weight vs Height")

grid.arrange(g2, g3, g4, g5, nrow = 1)

8. a nice graph using a combination of options

g2 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = Height, y = Weight)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2, aes(color = factor(Sex), shape = factor(Sex))) + 
  geom_smooth(aes(color = factor(Sex)), method = "lm",se = TRUE) + 
  scale_color_manual(name = "Sex", labels = c("Female","Male"), values = c("red", "blue")) +
  scale_shape_manual(name = "Sex", labels = c("Female","Male"), values = c(0, 2)) + 
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 8),
        axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 8), 
        plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = "black", size = 10),
        legend.position = c(1, 1), legend.justification = c(1, 1)) + 
  labs(x = "Height(in)",y = "Weight(lb)", title = "Linear Regression (95% CI) of Weight vs Height by Sex")

g2

Barplots

1. Basic barplot

ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex))) + geom_bar(stat = "count")

2. Horizontal bars, colors, width of bars

# 1. horizontal bars
p1 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight)) + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean,geom = "bar") + coord_flip()

# 2. change colors of bars
p2 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight, fill = factor(Sex))) + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean,geom = "bar") + scale_fill_manual(values = c("orangered", "royalblue"))

# 3. change width of bars
p3 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight)) + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean,geom = "bar", aes(width = 0.5))
## Warning: Ignoring unknown aesthetics: width
grid.arrange(p1,                             # First row with one plot spaning over 2 columns
             arrangeGrob(p2, p3, ncol = 2),  # Second row with 2 plots in 2 different columns
             nrow = 2)                       # Number of rows

3. Split and color by another variable

my_data$Height_category <- c('Median')
my_data$Height_category[my_data$Height > quantile(my_data$Height, 0.75)] <- c('Tall')
my_data$Height_category[my_data$Height < quantile(my_data$Height, 0.25)] <- c('Small')

# 1. next to each other
p1 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight, fill = factor(Height_category)), color = factor(Height_category)) +
stat_summary(fun.y = mean, position = position_dodge(), geom = "bar")

# 2. stacked
p2 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight, fill = factor(Height_category)), color = factor(Height_category)) +
stat_summary(fun.y = mean, position = "stack", geom = "bar")

# 3. with facets
p3 <- ggplot(my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = Weight, fill = factor(Height_category)), color = factor(Height_category)) +
stat_summary(fun.y = mean, geom = "bar") + facet_wrap(~Height_category)

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, nrow = 3)

5. Add error bars

summary.my_data <- data.frame(Sex = levels(as.factor(my_data$Sex)), 
                              mean_Wt = tapply(my_data$Weight,my_data$Sex, mean), 
                              sd_Wt = tapply(my_data$Weight, my_data$Sex, sd))
summary.my_data
##   Sex   mean_Wt    sd_Wt
## f   f  98.87838 18.61600
## m   m 103.44841 19.96806
ggplot(summary.my_data, aes(x = factor(Sex), y = mean_Wt)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", fill = "lightblue") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(50,130)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_Wt - sd_Wt, ymax = mean_Wt + sd_Wt), width = 0.3, color = "darkblue")

6. Add best fit line

# summarize data
summary.my_data2 <- data.frame(ht = levels(as.factor(my_data$Height)), 
                               mean_wt = tapply(my_data$Weight, my_data$Height, mean))

levels(as.factor(my_data$Height))

## [11] "55.5" "55.8" "56"   "56.3" "56.5" "56.8" "57"   "57.3" "57.5" "57.8"
## [21] "58"   "58.3" "58.5" "58.8" "59"   "59.3" "59.5" "59.8" "60"   "60.3"
## [31] "60.5" "60.8" "61"   "61.3" "61.5" "61.8" "62"   "62.3" "62.5" "62.8"
## [41] "63"   "63.3" "63.5" "63.8" "64"   "64.3" "64.5" "64.8" "65"   "65.3"
## [51] "65.5" "65.8" "66"   "66.3" "66.5" "66.8" "67"   "67.3" "67.5" "67.8"
## [61] "68"   "68.3" "68.5" "69"   "69.5" "69.8" "71"   "72"
# run a model
l <- summary(lm(mean_wt ~ as.numeric(ht), data = summary.my_data2))

# manually entering the intercept and slope
f1 <- ggplot(summary.my_data2, aes(x = factor(ht), y = mean_wt)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "darkblue") + 
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = l$coef[1, 1], slope = l$coef[2, 1]), color = "red", size = 1.5)

# using stat_smooth to fit the line for you
f2 <- ggplot(summary.my_data2, aes(x = factor(ht), y = mean_wt)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "darkblue") + 
  stat_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "orange", size = 1.5)

grid.arrange(f1, f2, nrow = 1)

Density plots

# basic density
p1 <- ggplot(xy, aes(xvar)) + geom_density()

# histogram with density line overlaid
p2 <- ggplot(xy, aes(x = xvar)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), color = "black", fill = NA) + geom_density(color = "blue")

# split and color by third variable, alpha fades the color a bit
p3 <- ggplot(xy, aes(xvar, fill = zvar)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.2)

Boxplots

# boxplot
b1 <- ggplot(xy, aes(zvar, xvar)) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill = zvar)) + theme(legend.position = "none")

# jitter plot
b2 <- ggplot(xy, aes(zvar, xvar)) + geom_jitter(alpha = I(1/4), aes(color = zvar)) + theme(legend.position = "none")

# violin plot
b3 <- ggplot(xy, aes(x = xvar)) + 
  stat_density(aes(ymax = ..density.., ymin = -..density.., fill = zvar, color = zvar), 
               geom = "ribbon", position = "identity") + 
  facet_grid(. ~ zvar) + coord_flip() + theme(legend.position = "none")

grid.arrange(b1, b2, b3, nrow = 1)

Putting multiple plots together

# rug plot
ggplot(xy, aes(xvar, yvar)) + geom_point() + geom_rug(col = "darkred", alpha = 0.1)

# placeholder plot - prints nothing at all
empty <- ggplot() + geom_point(aes(1, 1), colour = "white") + 
  theme(plot.background = element_blank(),panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(), axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank())

# scatterplot of x and y variables
scatter <- ggplot(xy, aes(xvar, yvar)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = zvar)) + scale_color_manual(values = c("orange","purple")) + 
  theme(legend.position = c(1, 1), legend.justification = c(1,1))

# marginal density of x - plot on top
plot_top <- ggplot(xy, aes(xvar, fill = zvar)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
scale_fill_manual(values = c("orange", "purple")) + theme(legend.position = "none")

# marginal density of y - plot on the right
plot_right <- ggplot(xy, aes(yvar, fill = zvar)) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  coord_flip() + scale_fill_manual(values = c("orange", "purple")) + theme(legend.position = "none")

# arrange the plots together, with appropriate height and width for each row and column
grid.arrange(plot_top, empty, scatter, plot_right, ncol = 2, nrow = 2, widths = c(4,1), heights = c(1, 4))
